## From source code (client.c / server.c)

Buffer sizes for now are 1001 and recvm are 1000 should i receive that much or just the 64 bytes i need?

### Code Organization
- [ ] Move shared structs to a header file (shared between client & server)
- [ ] Add #define constants: no magic numbers (max username len, roomname len,
      max rooms, buffer sizes, ICMP struct size)
- [ ] Extract add_user logic into its own reusable function (duplicated in server.c)
- [ ] Remove debug helper function in server.c (marked "remove after")

### Client
- [ ] Use poll() to handle concurrent stdin + socket reads simultaneously
- [ ] Add IP address validation on connect
- [ ] Add message buffer split: if msg > 100 chars, send remainder in next packet
      instead of losing data
- [ ] Fix terminal scramble when a message arrives while user is typing
- [ ] Handle Ctrl+C: graceful disconnect from server
- [ ] Move recv buffer allocation outside the while loop (avoid re-init cost)
- [ ] Handle PING from server: reply PONG (ICMP_ECHO_REPLY), do not print to screen

### Server
- [ ] Add max rooms limit to prevent OOM/DDoS via room creation
- [ ] Add overflow protection on roomname (> 10 chars overflows)
- [ ] Implement cleanup(): remove stale users (last_seen > 10s)
- [ ] Implement send_all_pings() called every ~5 seconds
- [ ] Re-zero recv buffer after each recvfrom to avoid stale data bleed
- [ ] Add packet validation / checksum to identify packets coming from our clients
      (e.g. use icmp_header->padding as a nonce/signature)
- [ ] Fix echo loop: server catches its own ICMP echo, not the reply from client
- [ ] Handle PONG reply from client (update last_seen, do not broadcast)

### Ping/Pong
- [ ] Solve kernel intercepting ICMP echo replies before client app sees them
      Options: use custom ICMP type, or disable kernel ping on client machine too


